{
  "texts": [
    "Notice that it is not possible to have consensus formation among inactive agents and, at the same time, opinion polarization among active ones, since the compromise dynamics are always stronger among active individuals.",
    "Finally, observe that as the value of ν p decreases, i.e.",
    "the compromise dynamics become more relevant, the value (ρ Ā(t) ± m Ā(t)) /ν p increases, which highlights again the importance of compromise processes to prevent opinion polarizations.",
    "In particular, ρ Ā(t) ≤ ω p + ε < 1 and we thus need small values of ν p to observe consensus formation (notice that the choice ν p < 1 could still lead to polarized opinions, see Figure 2).",
    "Consider now the sole interactions with opinion leaders, namely only the collisional operator (15)."
  ]
}